entry.title: BrowserLoader: Wait stateful lacros installation when enforced by policy
entry.content:
This CL lets BrowserLoader wait until stateful lacros to be installed

when the selection policy enforces the loader to load stateful lacros.



In production usage, lacros falls back to rootfs lacros when stateful

lacros is not yet ready and run installation of stateful lacros in the

background. However, for a debugging and testing purpose, the user can

set selection policy to enforce which lacros selection to use. In such

case, we cannot fallback to rootfs lacros, so we should wait the

installation to complete.



Bug: 1475689

entry.title: Correct PrintingContextWin error handling for enumerating printers
entry.content:
If the Windows print spooler is disabled then the GDI call to

EnumPrinters() fails. In this case the return value shows failure and

the error code shows the server is not available. The GDI call also

modifies the provided out parameters: the count of printers is set to

zero and the bytes needed is set to some random value, which looks like

it is an uninitialized value.



Since the error handling in PrintingContextWin::UseDefaultSettings()

was only relying upon the bytes needed value, this can result in

out-of-memory errors by trying to use the uninitialized value to

allocate the printer info buffer.



Modify the basic error checking around the EnumPrinters() call to mimic

what is done in PrintBackendWin::EnumeratePrinters(), which correctly

addresses this situation. Do not have PrintingContextWin directly use

PrintBackendWin, as that would incur extra overhead, given that

PrintingContextWin is only interested in the first possible printer and

not all of them.

entry.title: Allow for 16 GiB PDBs and debug component builds
entry.content:
Originally Chrome's PDBs could be a maximum of 4 GiB. That limit became

constraining and support for larger PDBs became available so the limit

was raised to 8 GiB. That is good enough for "normal" use, but when

doing debug non-component builds the PDB for chrome.dll gets very close

to 8 GiB, and browser_tests.exe.pdb is about 9.6 GiB.



Changing from an 8 KiB page size to 16 KiB page size lets us support

PDBs up to 16 GiB which should be enough for the foreeseable future. The

only known cost is that PDBs get about 2.3% larger. By only using the

16 KiB page size for debug non-component builds we can avoid paying

this cost when we don't need to.



With 16 GiB PDBs the formerly unsupported debug non-component build

flavor becomes supportable. Link times are still slow (almost two

minutes on my chrome.dll.pdb tests) but the debugging experience can be

superior in some cases.



Prior to this change the debug non-component build was accidentally

supported on Windows, but only if the NOP flag use_debug_fission=true

was set. Now this configuration is intentionally and properly supported.



A debug component build is desirable because some types are defined

in one component (DLL in Windows) and used in another component. In

this situation there is no type information for the type in the DLL

where the type is used, so the debugger can't show the object

internals. This makes for a bad debugging experience.



The debug component builds are slow to build and debug, so they won't

be catching on anytime soon, but for some problems they are

invaluable.

entry.title: Create a handle system for UI objects.
entry.content:
An object that |SupportsHandles| allows you to call GetHandle() to return a handle to that object. Handles are opaque objects that are serializable but from which the original object can be retrieved if it still exists.



The integral type for the opaque handle may be specified in order to ensure adequate bits for the rolling counter, and the behavior when the counter rolls over can also be specified. The fact that rollover is possible is the major disadvantage vs. |WeakPtr|, which is almost always the better choice if you do not need serializability.



This is a prerequisite for a lot of stability work we are doing in

the tabstrip model and related systems.

entry.title: [A11y] Don't detach an object while updating its cached values
entry.content:
When detaching an object from a parent, we sometimes destroy its

subtree as well, if the subtree only makes sense in the context of its

parent. This is true for image map areas, but our check for that was

not tight enough. As a result, an object inside of a role=image

could be destroyed by a chain of recursive cached value updates that

ends up calling SetNeedsToUpdateChildren() on the parent.

The fix for this is sufficient to fix the repro

case in the bug, but it may not fix all cases of the bug.



Therefore, in lieu of a test, a new check has been added to ensure

that an object will not be detached while in the middle of updating its

cached values, so if there are more instances of the issue, we will get

more useful stacks and information.



Fixed: 1480267

entry.title: Don't save snap fraction too early for ARC
entry.content:
With crrev.com/c/4713908, PiP snap fraction is saved for the first

time in OnWindowVisibilityChanged(). This is done here because

in most cases PiP gets visible after everything is set up for the

window, but it turns out in the case of an ARC window getting into

PiP from minimized, visibility is updated when window state change

happens, which is too early because at this point the bounds for

PiP hasn't been set yet.



For ARC PiP, snap fraction is saved in

ClientControlledShellSurface::OnPostWidgetCommit(), where an ARC

window is fully ready for PiP, so for ARC PiP, we should skip

setting snap fraction in OnWindowVisibilityChanged().

entry.title: [Safe Browsing] Refactor protego ping logging logic
entry.content:
The logic to record the most recent protego ping value was implicitly

dependent on whether the preference service had been provided to the url

lookup service. For now, this worked because the enterprise version of

the service did not provide a the preference service. This was brittle,

however, because if someone decided to supply a preference service to

the `ChromeEnterpriseRealTimeUrlLookupService`, they would inadvertently

cause that service to start logging protego pings.



To make this code more robust, we introduce a new virtual method that

the base class provides an empty implementation for. Then any sub-class

that wants to implement the functionality can do so. In this case, we

moved the implementation to the `RealTimeUrlLookupService` class.

entry.title: Handle OOFs in spanners within NGOutOfFlowLayoutPart::ReplaceFragment
entry.content:
When we find an OOF in the CB path within

NGOutOfFlowLayoutPart::ReplaceFragment(), we end up looking for the

next viable fragmentation context root to search for its fragment(s).

However, if there is a spanner in the CB path (as a result of

CL:3343283), that OOF will propagate up to the next context since

spanners are not laid out in their immediate multicol parent.



Thus, we will need to continue up the tree in such cases in

NGOutOfFlowLayoutPart::ReplaceFragment() in order to properly find

the OOF ancestor in question.

entry.title: Allow multiple SparseHistograms per sparse histogram data manager
entry.content:
The strategy is that there is one "data manager"

("PersistentSparseHistogramDataManager"), which is the source of

truth, and knows about the samples for all sparse histograms. A sparse

histogram may request its own "PersistentSampleMapRecords" from the

"data manager", which basically just replicates the "data manager"

as needed.



This refactoring should have practically no performance penalties,

neither in terms of time nor space (maybe just a tiny bit more space,

but this is trivial). This is not a no-op -- the restriction for only

one SparseHistogram instance per histogram is now gone.



Also updates various tests (threadsafe, allocator, subprocess) to

make sure this works properly. These updated tests fail without

these changes, and pass with the changes.

> Speculative fix for potential UAF in overlay_window_views .

>

> It looks like the WindowAndroid has been destroyed before the

> overlay window is destroyed in some cases. It's not clear what's

> going on, but there is at least one path where the overlay window

> would be unsubscribed from WindowAndroid callbacks without realizing

> it. In that case, we might try to unregister later.

>

> I wasn't able to repro this path locally, unfortunately.

>

> Further, it might be the case that we should initiate cleanup of

> the overlay window in this case, but this CL doesn't go that far.

> If the crashes subside, then it might be worth more effort to

> figure out what's getting into this state and what the appropriate

> response is. As it is, it's all speculation, so simpler is better.

entry.title: [iOS] Fix ordering of overflow menu model initialization calls
entry.content:
This was causing a small bug where feature-provided badges weren't being

cleared because that happens as part of the call to

`-reorderDestinationsForInitialMenu`, but during `-updateModel`, the

badges were being added to the destinations, so once the reorder call

came around, the orderer thought that the badges were still there.



This CL fixes that by splitting `-updateModel` up into two parts, one

to update the state of the individual items (which can then be called

before the initial reorder), and one to update any other orderings (e.g.

order of actions, order of other groups), which can be called

afterwards.

entry.title: [DSE] Disable Start surface according to DSE's new tab url.
entry.content:
In this CL, ReturnToChromeUtil#isStartSurfaceEnabled() checks if

swap out NTP according to DSE is enabled. If true, Start surface will

be disabled and no longer shown at startup. Since

#isStartSurfaceEnabled() is checked at startup, the newly added checks

only query the cached value in the SharedPreference, rather than

the TemplateUrlService. This allows the API always returns the same

value in the same session that Chrome is running.

reflect the specs:

entry.title: [X-Device Restore] Fix unexpected omnibox focus on tab switcher V3
entry.content:
Third attempt at fixing unexpected omnibox focus when transitioning between the tab switcher and a tab page.



Set focusability to false on the omnibox only when entering the tab switcher, and guard the pre-existing set to true call to only when the tab switcher has finished exiting.



The second attempt caused the omnibox focus to be false in a specific scenario (crbug.com/1479883) when the user closes the app without leaving the tab switcher. It seems the ToolbarManager is incorrectly setting the tab switcher mode to true on return when it's on the start surface, so that change has been amended here.
